[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In mathematics, the **bisection method** is a root-finding method that applies to any continuous function for which one knows two values with opposite signs.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The method consists of repeatedly bisecting the interval defined by these values, then selecting the subinterval in which the function changes sign, which therefore must contain a root.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] It is a very simple and robust method, but it is also relatively slow.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Because of this, it is often used to obtain a rough approximation to a solution which is then used as a starting point for more rapidly converging methods.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The method is also called the **interval halving** method, the **binary search method**, or the **dichotomy method**.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] For polynomials, more elaborate methods exist for testing the existence of a root in an interval (Descartes' rule of signs, Sturm's theorem, Budan's theorem).
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] They allow extending the bisection method into efficient algorithms for finding all real roots of a polynomial; see Real-root isolation.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The method is applicable for numerically solving the equation $f(x)=0$ for the real variable x , where f is a continuous function defined on an interval $[a,b]$ and where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In this case a and b are said to bracket a root since, by the intermediate value theorem, the continuous function f must have at least one root in the interval $(a,b)$ .
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] At each step the method divides the interval in two parts/halves by computing the midpoint $c=(a+b)/2$ of the interval and the value of the function $f(c)$ at that point.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] If c itself is a root then the process has succeeded and stops.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Otherwise, there are now only two possibilities: either $f(a)$ and $f(c)$ have opposite signs and bracket a root, or $f(c)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs and bracket a root.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The method selects the subinterval that is guaranteed to be a bracket as the new interval to be used in the next step.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In this way an interval that contains a zero of f is reduced in width by 50% at each step.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The process is continued until the interval is sufficiently small.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Explicitly, if $f(c)=0$ then c may be taken as the solution and the process stops.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In both cases, the new $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, so the method may be applied to this smaller interval.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Once the process starts, the signs at the left and right ends of the interval remain the same for all iterations.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In order to determine when the iteration should stop, it is necessary to consider various possible stopping conditions with respect to a tolerance ( $\epsilon$ ).
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] $|f(p_{N})|<\epsilon$ does not give an accurate result to within $\epsilon$ unless $|f'(p_{N})|\geq 1$ .
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The other two possibilities represent different concepts: the absolute difference $|c-a|\leq 5\times 10^{-t}$ says that c and a are the same to t decimal places, while the relative difference $\left|{\frac {c-a}{c}}\right|\leq 5\times 10^{-t}$ says that c and a are the same to t significant figures.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] If nothing is known about the value of the root, then relative tolerance is the best stopping condition.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The input for the method is a continuous function f and an interval $[a,b]$ , such that the function values $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ are of opposite sign (there is at least one zero crossing within the interval).
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Examine the sign of $f(c)$ and replace either a or b with c so that there is a zero crossing within the new interval.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] First, two numbers a and b have to be found such that $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Because the function is continuous, there must be a root within the interval [1, 2].
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] After 13 iterations, it becomes apparent that there is a convergence to about 1.521: a root for the polynomial.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The bisection method has been generalized to multi-dimensional functions.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Such methods are called **generalized bisection methods**.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Some of these methods are based on computing the topological degree.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] The **characteristic bisection method** uses only the signs of a function in different points.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Lef *f* be a function from R*d* to R*d*, for some integer *d* ≥ 2.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] A **characteristic polyhedron** (also called an **admissible polygon**) of *f* is a polyhedron in R*d*, having 2*d* vertices, such that in each vertex **v**, the combination of signs of *f*(**v**) is unique.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] A **proper edge** of a characteristic polygon is a edge between a pair of vertices, such that the sign vector differs by only a single sign.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In the above example, the proper edges of the characteristic quadrilateral are AB, AC, BD and CD.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] A **diagonal** is a pair of vertices, such that the sign vector differs by all *d* signs.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] In the above example, the diagonals are AD and BC.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] At each iteration, the algorithm picks a proper edge of the polyhedron (say, A—B), and computes the signs of *f* in its mid-point (say, M).
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Suppose the diameter (= length of longest proper edge) of the original characteristic polyhedron is D.
[src:numerical-methods/bisection-method] Then, at least $\log _{2}(D/\varepsilon )$ bisections of edges are required so that the diameter of the remaining polygon will be at most $\varepsilon$ .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] In numerical analysis, the **condition number** of a function measures how much the output value of the function can change for a small change in the input argument.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] This is used to measure how sensitive a function is to changes or errors in the input, and how much error in the output results from an error in the input.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Very frequently, one is solving the inverse problem: given $f(x)=y,$ one is solving for *x,* and thus the condition number of the (local) inverse must be used.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number is derived from the theory of propagation of uncertainty, and is formally defined as the value of the asymptotic worst-case relative change in output for a relative change in input.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The "function" is the solution of a problem and the "arguments" are the data in the problem.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number is frequently applied to questions in linear algebra, in which case the derivative is straightforward but the error could be in many different directions, and is thus computed from the geometry of the matrix.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] More generally, condition numbers can be defined for non-linear functions in several variables.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] A problem with a low condition number is said to be ***well-conditioned***, while a problem with a high condition number is said to be ***ill-conditioned***.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] In non-mathematical terms, an ill-conditioned problem is one where, for a small change in the inputs (the independent variables) there is a large change in the answer or dependent variable.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] This means that the correct solution/answer to the equation becomes hard to find.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number is a property of the problem.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Paired with the problem are any number of algorithms that can be used to solve the problem, that is, to calculate the solution.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Some algorithms have a property called *backward stability*; in general, a backward stable algorithm can be expected to accurately solve well-conditioned problems.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Numerical analysis textbooks give formulas for the condition numbers of problems and identify known backward stable algorithms.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] As a rule of thumb, if the condition number $\kappa (A)=10^{k}$ , then up to k digits of accuracy may be lost on top of what would be lost to the numerical method due to loss of precision from arithmetic methods.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] However, the condition number does not give the exact value of the maximum inaccuracy that may occur in the algorithm.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] It generally just bounds it with an estimate (whose computed value depends on the choice of the norm to measure the inaccuracy).
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] For example, the condition number associated with the linear equation *Ax* = *b* gives a bound on how inaccurate the solution *x* will be after approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Note that this is before the effects of round-off error are taken into account; conditioning is a property of the matrix, not the algorithm or floating-point accuracy of the computer used to solve the corresponding system.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] In particular, one should think of the condition number as being (very roughly) the rate at which the solution *x* will change with respect to a change in *b*.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Thus, if the condition number is large, even a small error in *b* may cause a large error in *x*.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] On the other hand, if the condition number is small, then the error in *x* will not be much bigger than the error in *b*.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number is defined more precisely to be the maximum ratio of the relative error in *x* to the relative error in *b*.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Assuming that *A* is a nonsingular matrix, the error in the solution *A*−1*b* is *A*−1*e*.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number may also be infinite, but this implies that the problem is ill-posed (does not possess a unique, well-defined solution for each choice of data; that is, the matrix is not invertible), and no algorithm can be expected to reliably find a solution.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The definition of the condition number depends on the choice of norm, as can be illustrated by two examples.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] where $\sigma _{\text{max}}(A)$ and $\sigma _{\text{min}}(A)$ are maximal and minimal singular values of A respectively.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number with respect to *L*2 arises so often in numerical linear algebra that it is given a name, the **condition number of a matrix**.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] recalling that the eigenvalues of any triangular matrix are simply the diagonal entries.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] If the condition number is not significantly larger than one, the matrix is well-conditioned, which means that its inverse can be computed with good accuracy.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] If the condition number is very large, then the matrix is said to be ill-conditioned.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Practically, such a matrix is almost singular, and the computation of its inverse, or solution of a linear system of equations is prone to large numerical errors.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] A matrix that is not invertible is often said to have a condition number equal to infinity.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Alternatively, it can be defined as $\kappa (A)=\|A\|\|A^{\dagger }\|$ , where $A^{\dagger }$ is the Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] For square matrices, this unfortunately makes the condition number discontinuous, but it is a useful definition for rectangular matrices, which are never invertible but are still used to define systems of equations.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Condition numbers can also be defined for nonlinear functions, and can be computed using calculus.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The condition number varies with the point; in some cases one can use the maximum (or supremum) condition number over the domain of the function or domain of the question as an overall condition number, while in other cases the condition number at a particular point is of more interest.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The *relative* condition number of f as a function is $\left|xf'/f\right|$ .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Note that this is the absolute value of the elasticity of a function in economics.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Most elegantly, this can be understood as (the absolute value of) the ratio of the logarithmic derivative of f , which is $(\log f)'=f'/f$ , and the logarithmic derivative of x , which is $(\log x)'=x'/x=1/x$ , yielding a ratio of $xf'/f$ .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] This is because the logarithmic derivative is the infinitesimal rate of relative change in a function: it is the derivative $f'$ scaled by the value of f .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Note that if a function has a zero at a point, its condition number at the point is infinite, as infinitesimal changes in the input can change the output from zero to positive or negative, yielding a ratio with zero in the denominator, hence infinite relative change.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] More directly, given a small change $\Delta x$ in x , the relative change in x is $[(x+\Delta x)-x]/x=(\Delta x)/x$ , while the relative change in $f(x)$ is $[f(x+\Delta x)-f(x)]/f(x)$ .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] The last term is the difference quotient (the slope of the secant line), and taking the limit yields the derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Condition numbers of common elementary functions are particularly important in computing significant figures and can be computed immediately from the derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] Condition numbers can be defined for any function f mapping its data from some domain (e.g. an m -tuple of real numbers x ) into some codomain (e.g. an n -tuple of real numbers $f(x)$ ), where both the domain and codomain are Banach spaces.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] They express how sensitive that function is to small changes (or small errors) in its arguments.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] This is crucial in assessing the sensitivity and potential accuracy difficulties of numerous computational problems, for example, polynomial root finding or computing eigenvalues.
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] where $\|\cdot \|$ is a norm on the domain/codomain of f .
[src:numerical-methods/condition-number] where ⁠ $J(x)$ ⁠ denotes the Jacobian matrix of partial derivatives of f at x , and $\|J(x)\|$ is the induced norm on the matrix.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] A **finite difference** is a mathematical expression of the form *f*(*x* + *b*) − *f*(*x* + *a*).
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Finite differences (or the associated difference quotients) are often used as approximations of derivatives, such as in numerical differentiation.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] There are many similarities between difference equations and differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Certain recurrence relations can be written as difference equations by replacing iteration notation with finite differences.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] In numerical analysis, finite differences are widely used for approximating derivatives, and the term "finite difference" is often used as an abbreviation of "finite difference approximation of derivatives".
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Finite differences were introduced by Brook Taylor in 1715 and have also been studied as abstract self-standing mathematical objects in works by George Boole (1860), L.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Finite differences trace their origins back to one of Jost Bürgi's algorithms (c.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] 1592) and work by others including Isaac Newton.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The formal calculus of finite differences can be viewed as an alternative to the calculus of infinitesimals.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Three basic types are commonly considered: *forward*, *backward*, and *central* finite differences.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Depending on the application, the spacing h may be variable or constant.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The approximation of derivatives by finite differences plays a central role in finite difference methods for the numerical solution of differential equations, especially boundary value problems.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Hence, the forward difference divided by h approximates the derivative when h is small.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The error in this approximation can be derived from Taylor's theorem.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] However, the central (also called centered) difference yields a more accurate approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The main problem with the central difference method, however, is that oscillating functions can yield zero derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] If *f*(*nh*) = 1 for n odd, and *f*(*nh*) = 2 for n even, then *f*′(*nh*) = 0 if it is calculated with the central difference scheme.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This is particularly troublesome if the domain of f is discrete.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Authors for whom finite differences mean finite difference approximations define the forward/backward/central differences as the quotients given in this section (instead of employing the definitions given in the previous section).
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] In an analogous way, one can obtain finite difference approximations to higher order derivatives and differential operators.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Similarly we can apply other differencing formulas in a recursive manner.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] These equations use binomial coefficients after the summation sign shown as ${\textstyle \ {\binom {n}{j}}~.}$ Each row of Pascal's triangle provides the coefficient for each value of j .
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Note that the central difference will, for odd n, have h multiplied by non-integers.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This is often a problem because it amounts to changing the interval of discretization.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Forward differences applied to a sequence are sometimes called the binomial transform of the sequence, and have a number of interesting combinatorial properties.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Forward differences may be evaluated using the Nörlund–Rice integral.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Higher-order differences can also be used to construct better approximations.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] As mentioned above, the first-order difference approximates the first-order derivative up to a term of order h.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This can be proven by expanding the above expression in Taylor series, or by using the calculus of finite differences, explained below.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] If necessary, the finite difference can be centered about any point by mixing forward, backward, and central differences.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Sometimes, the low order derivatives of a function may be analytically known, but high order derivatives are not.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] In these cases, the high order derivatives can be approximated by finite difference of low order derivatives, which is often more accurate and numerically more stable than finite difference of the function *f* (*x*) itself.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This is sometimes called seminumerical differentiation.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Only the coefficient of the highest-order term remains.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] As this result is constant with respect to *x*, any further pairwise differences will have the value 0.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Let *R*(*x*) be a polynomial of degree *m* − 1 where *m* ≥ 2 and the coefficient of the highest-order term be *a* ≠ 0.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Let *S*(*x*) be a polynomial of degree *m*.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] As *ahm* ≠ 0, this results in a polynomial *T*(*x*) of degree *m* − 1, with *ahm* as the coefficient of the highest-order term.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This identity can be used to find the lowest-degree polynomial that intercepts a number of points (*x*, *y*) where the difference on the *x*-axis from one point to the next is a constant *h* ≠ 0.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The arithmetic difference is *h* = 3, as established above.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Given the number of pairwise differences needed to reach the constant, it can be surmised this is a polynomial of degree 3.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Solving for *a*, it can be found to have the value 4.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Thus, the first term of the polynomial is 4*x*3.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Solving for *a*, which is −17, the polynomial's second term is −17*x*2.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] It can be found that *a* = 36 and thus the third term of the polynomial is **36*x***.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Without any pairwise differences, it is found that the 4th and final term of the polynomial is the constant −19.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Using linear algebra one can construct finite difference approximations which utilize an arbitrary number of points to the left and a (possibly different) number of points to the right of the evaluation point, for any order derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This involves solving a linear system such that the Taylor expansion of the sum of those points around the evaluation point best approximates the Taylor expansion of the desired derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Such formulas can be represented graphically on a hexagonal or diamond-shaped grid.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This is useful for differentiating a function on a grid, where, as one approaches the edge of the grid, one must sample fewer and fewer points on one side.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Finite difference approximations for non-standard (and even non-integer) stencils given an arbitrary stencil and a desired derivative order may be constructed.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] An important application of finite differences is in numerical analysis, especially in numerical differential equations, which aim at the numerical solution of ordinary and partial differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The idea is to replace the derivatives appearing in the differential equation by finite differences that approximate them.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The resulting methods are called finite difference methods.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Common applications of the finite difference method are in computational science and engineering disciplines, such as thermal engineering, fluid mechanics, etc.
