[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Historically, this, as well as the Chu–Vandermonde identity, $(x+y)_{n}=\sum _{k=0}^{n}{\binom {n}{k}}(x)_{n-k}\,(y)_{k},$ (following from it, and corresponding to the binomial theorem), are included in the observations that matured to the system of umbral calculus.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Newton series expansions can be superior to Taylor series expansions when applied to discrete quantities like quantum spins (see Holstein–Primakoff transformation), bosonic operator functions or discrete counting statistics.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] To illustrate how one may use Newton's formula in actual practice, consider the first few terms of doubling the Fibonacci sequence *f* = 2, 2, 4, ...
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] In analysis with p-adic numbers, Mahler's theorem states that the assumption that f is a polynomial function can be weakened all the way to the assumption that f is merely continuous.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Carlson's theorem provides necessary and sufficient conditions for a Newton series to be unique, if it exists.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] However, a Newton series does not, in general, exist.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The Newton series, together with the Stirling series and the Selberg series, is a special case of the general difference series, all of which are defined in terms of suitably scaled forward differences.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The forward difference can be considered as an operator, called the difference operator, which maps the function f to Δ*h*[*f*].
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This operator amounts to $\Delta _{h}=\operatorname {T} _{h}-\operatorname {I} ,$ where T*h* is the shift operator with step h, defined by T*h*[*f*](*x*) = *f*(*x* + *h*), and I is the identity operator.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The finite difference of higher orders can be defined in recursive manner as Δ*n* *h* ≡ Δ*h*(Δ*n* − 1 *h*).
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Another equivalent definition is Δ*n* *h* ≡ [T*h* − I]*n*.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Similar Leibniz rules hold for the backward and central differences.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The expansion is valid when both sides act on analytic functions, for sufficiently small h; in the special case that the series of derivatives terminates (when the function operated on is a finite polynomial) the expression is exact, for *all* finite stepsizes, h .
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Thus T*h* = *e**h* D, and formally inverting the exponential yields $h\operatorname {D} =\ln(1+\Delta _{h})=\Delta _{h}-{\tfrac {1}{2}}\,\Delta _{h}^{2}+{\tfrac {1}{3}}\,\Delta _{h}^{3}-\cdots ~.$ This formula holds in the sense that both operators give the same result when applied to a polynomial.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Even for analytic functions, the series on the right is not guaranteed to converge; it may be an asymptotic series.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] However, it can be used to obtain more accurate approximations for the derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] For instance, retaining the first two terms of the series yields the second-order approximation to *f* ′(*x*) mentioned at the end of the section *§ Higher-order differences*.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The calculus of finite differences is related to the umbral calculus of combinatorics.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] A large number of formal differential relations of standard calculus involving functions *f*(*x*) thus *systematically map to umbral finite-difference analogs* involving *f*( *x* T−1 *h* ).
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] and hence *Fourier sums of continuum functions are readily, faithfully mapped to umbral Fourier sums*, i.e., involving the same Fourier coefficients multiplying these umbral basis exponentials.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] This umbral exponential thus amounts to the exponential generating function of the Pochhammer symbols.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Thus, for instance, the Dirac delta function maps to its umbral correspondent, the cardinal sine function $\delta (x)\mapsto {\frac {\sin \left[{\frac {\pi }{2}}\left(1+{\frac {x}{h}}\right)\right]}{\pi (x+h)}},$ and so forth.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Difference equations can often be solved with techniques very similar to those for solving differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] The inverse operator of the forward difference operator, so then the umbral integral, is the indefinite sum or antidifference operator.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] All of the above rules apply equally well to any difference operator as to Δ, including δ and ∇.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] Finite differences can be considered in more than one variable.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] They are analogous to partial derivatives in several variables.
[src:numerical-methods/finite-difference] However, for many classes of functions, the m -th order derivative tensor is sparse, or its off-diagonal blocks may have low rank.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:numerical-methods/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:numerical-methods/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In numerical analysis, the **Newton–Raphson method**, also known simply as **Newton's method**, named after Isaac Newton and Joseph Raphson, is a root-finding algorithm which produces successively better approximations to the roots (or zeroes) of a real-valued function.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The most basic version starts with a real-valued function f, its derivative f′, and an initial guess *x*0 for a root of f.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] is a better approximation of the root than *x*0.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Geometrically, (*x*1, 0) is the x-intercept of the tangent to the graph of f at (*x*0, *f*(*x*0)): that is, the improved guess, *x*1, is the unique root of the linear approximation of f at the initial guess, *x*0.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] until a sufficiently precise value is reached.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The number of correct digits roughly doubles with each step.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This algorithm is first in the class of Householder's methods, and was succeeded by Halley's method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The method can also be extended to complex functions and to systems of equations.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The purpose of Newton's method is to find a root of a function.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The idea is to start with an initial guess near a root, approximate the function by its tangent line near the guess, and then take the root of the linear approximation as a next guess at the function's root.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This will typically be closer to the function's root than the previous guess, and the method can be iterated.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The process can be started with any arbitrary initial guess ⁠ x 0 {\displaystyle x_{0}} ({\displaystyle x_{0}})⁠, though it will generally require fewer iterations to converge if the guess is close to one of the function's roots.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Furthermore, for a root of multiplicity 1, the convergence is at least quadratic (see *Rate of convergence*) in some sufficiently small neighbourhood of the root: the number of correct digits of the approximation roughly doubles with each additional step.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] More details can be found in *§ Analysis* below.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Householder's methods are similar but have higher order for even faster convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, the extra computations required for each step can slow down the overall performance relative to Newton's method, particularly if ⁠ f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f})⁠ or its derivatives are computationally expensive to evaluate.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Jamshīd al-Kāshī used a method to solve *x**P* − *N* = 0 to find roots of *N*, a method that was algebraically equivalent to Newton's method, and in which a similar method was found in *Trigonometria Britannica*, published by Henry Briggs in 1633.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] His method first appeared in his 1427 publication *Miftāḥ al-Ḥisāb* (*The Key to Arithmetic*).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Al-Kāshī's work was founded on the earlier contributions of the polymath al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) and the mathematician Sharaf al-Dīn al-Ṭūsī (1135–1213).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The contributions of al-Kāshī remained largely unknown to the Western scientific community for centuries, until the work of François Viète (1540–1603).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In 1600, Viète rediscovered a technique similar to al-Kāshī's in the context of solving scalar polynomial equations of degree six.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, while Newton gave the basic ideas, his method differs from the modern method given above.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] He applied the method only to polynomials, starting with an initial root estimate and extracting a sequence of error corrections.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] He used each correction to rewrite the polynomial in terms of the remaining error, and then solved for a new correction by neglecting higher-degree terms.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] He did not explicitly connect the method with derivatives or present a general formula.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton applied this method to both numerical and algebraic problems, producing Taylor series in the latter case.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Despite this, in the later second and third editions of Newton's 1687 *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, he did apply his method in an iterative manner to a nonpolynomial equation, specifically Kepler's equation, which were the first published uses of Newton's method in this form by him.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton may have derived his method from a similar, less precise method by mathematician Viète, however, the two methods are not the same.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The essence of Viète's own method can be found in the work of the mathematician Sharaf al-Din al-Tusi.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The Japanese mathematician Seki Kōwa used a form of Newton's method in the 1680s to solve single-variable equations, though the connection with calculus was missing.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton's method was first published in 1685 in *A Treatise of Algebra both Historical and Practical* by John Wallis.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In 1690, Raphson published a simplified description in *Analysis aequationum universalis*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Raphson also applied the method only to polynomials, but he avoided Newton's tedious rewriting process by extracting each successive correction from the original polynomial.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This allowed him to derive a reusable iterative expression for each problem.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Finally, in 1740, Simpson described Newton's method as an iterative method for solving general nonlinear equations using calculus, essentially giving the description above.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In the same publication, Simpson also gives the generalization to systems of two equations and notes that Newton's method can be used for solving optimization problems by setting the gradient to zero.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Arthur Cayley in 1879 in *The Newton–Fourier imaginary problem* was the first to notice the difficulties in generalizing Newton's method to complex roots of polynomials with degree greater than 2 and complex initial values.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This opened the way to the study of the theory of iterations of rational functions.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, there are some difficulties with the method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton's method requires that the derivative can be calculated directly.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] An analytical expression for the derivative may not be easily obtainable or could be expensive to evaluate.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In these situations, it may be appropriate to approximate the derivative by using the slope of a line through two nearby points on the function.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Using this approximation would result in something like the secant method whose convergence is slower than that of Newton's method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] It is important to review the proof of quadratic convergence of Newton's method before implementing it.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Specifically, one should review the assumptions made in the proof.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For situations where the method fails to converge, it is because the assumptions made in this proof are not met.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For example, in some cases, if the first derivative is not well behaved in the neighborhood of a particular root, then it is possible that Newton's method will fail to converge no matter where the initialization is set.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In some cases, Newton's method can be stabilized by using successive over-relaxation, or the speed of convergence can be increased by using the same method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In a robust implementation of Newton's method, it is common to place limits on the number of iterations, bound the solution to an interval known to contain the root, and combine the method with a more robust root finding method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If the root being sought has multiplicity greater than one, the convergence rate is merely linear (errors reduced by a constant factor at each step) unless special steps are taken.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] When there are two or more roots that are close together then it may take many iterations before the iterates get close enough to one of them for the quadratic convergence to be apparent.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This is equivalent to using successive over-relaxation.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] On the other hand, if the multiplicity m of the root is not known, it is possible to estimate m after carrying out one or two iterations, and then use that value to increase the rate of convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If the multiplicity m of the root is finite then *g*(*x*) = ⁠*f*(*x*)/*f′*(*x*)⁠ will have a root at the same location with multiplicity 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Applying Newton's method to find the root of *g*(*x*) recovers quadratic convergence in many cases although it generally involves the second derivative of *f*(*x*).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The function *f*(*x*) = *x*2 has a root at 0.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Since f is continuously differentiable at its root, the theory guarantees that Newton's method as initialized sufficiently close to the root will converge.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, since the derivative *f* ′ is zero at the root, quadratic convergence is not ensured by the theory.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] It is visible from this that Newton's method could be initialized anywhere and converge to zero, but at only a linear rate.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If initialized at 1, dozens of iterations would be required before ten digits of accuracy are achieved.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The function *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*4/3 also has a root at 0, where it is continuously differentiable.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Although the first derivative *f* ′ is nonzero at the root, the second derivative *f* ′′ is nonexistent there, so that quadratic convergence cannot be guaranteed.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] From this, it can be seen that the rate of convergence is superlinear but subquadratic.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This can be seen in the following tables, the left of which shows Newton's method applied to the above *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*4/3 and the right of which shows Newton's method applied to *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*2.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The quadratic convergence in iteration shown on the right is illustrated by the orders of magnitude in the distance from the iterate to the true root (0,1,2,3,5,10,20,39,...) being approximately doubled from row to row.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] While the convergence on the left is superlinear, the order of magnitude is only multiplied by about 4/3 from row to row (0,1,2,4,5,7,10,13,...).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The rate of convergence is distinguished from the number of iterations required to reach a given accuracy.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For example, the function *f*(*x*) = *x*20 − 1 has a root at 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Since *f* ′(1) ≠ 0 and f is smooth, it is known that any Newton iteration convergent to 1 will converge quadratically.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, if initialized at 0.5, the first few iterates of Newton's method are approximately 26214, 24904, 23658, 22476, decreasing slowly, with only the 200th iterate being 1.0371.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This highlights that quadratic convergence of a Newton iteration does not mean that only few iterates are required; this only applies once the sequence of iterates is sufficiently close to the root.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] From this, it can be seen that there are three possible phenomena for a Newton iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If initialized strictly between ±1, the Newton iteration will converge (super-)quadratically to 0; if initialized exactly at 1 or −1, the Newton iteration will oscillate endlessly between ±1; if initialized anywhere else, the Newton iteration will diverge.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This same trichotomy occurs for *f*(*x*) = arctan *x*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In cases where the function in question has multiple roots, it can be difficult to control, via choice of initialization, which root (if any) is identified by Newton's method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If initialized at −1.488, the Newton iteration converges to 0; if initialized at −1.487, it diverges to ∞; if initialized at −1.486, it converges to −1; if initialized at −1.485, it diverges to −∞; if initialized at −1.4843, it converges to 3; if initialized at −1.484, it converges to 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This kind of subtle dependence on initialization is not uncommon; it is frequently studied in the complex plane in the form of the Newton fractal.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Consider the problem of finding a root of *f*(*x*) = *x*1/3.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Unless Newton's method is initialized at the exact root 0, it is seen that the sequence of iterates will fail to converge.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This failure of convergence is not contradicted by the analytic theory, since in this case f is not differentiable at its root.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In the above example, failure of convergence is reflected by the failure of *f*(*x**n*) to get closer to zero as n increases, as well as by the fact that successive iterates are growing further and further apart.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In this example, where again f is not differentiable at the root, any Newton iteration not starting exactly at the root will diverge, but with both *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* and *f*(*x**n*) converging to zero.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Although the convergence of *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* in this case is not very rapid, it can be proved from the iteration formula.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This example highlights the possibility that a stopping criterion for Newton's method based only on the smallness of *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* and *f*(*x**n*) might falsely identify a root.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] It is easy to find situations for which Newton's method oscillates endlessly between two distinct values.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For example, for Newton's method as applied to a function f to oscillate between 0 and 1, it is only necessary that the tangent line to f at 0 intersects the x-axis at 1 and that the tangent line to f at 1 intersects the x-axis at 0.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For this function, it is even the case that Newton's iteration as initialized sufficiently close to 0 or 1 will *asymptotically* oscillate between these values.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This behavior is present despite the presence of a root of f approximately equal to −1.76929.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In some cases, it is not even possible to perform the Newton iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] So Newton's method cannot be initialized at 0, since this would make *x*1 undefined.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Geometrically, this is because the tangent line to f at 0 is horizontal (i.e.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Even if the initialization is selected so that the Newton iteration can begin, the same phenomenon can block the iteration from being indefinitely continued.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If f has an incomplete domain, it is possible for Newton's method to send the iterates outside of the domain, so that it is impossible to continue the iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] For example, the natural logarithm function *f*(*x*) = ln *x* has a root at 1, and is defined only for positive x.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] So if the iteration is initialized at e, the next iterate is 0; if the iteration is initialized at a value larger than e, then the next iterate is negative.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In either case, the method cannot be continued.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Suppose that the function f has a zero at α, i.e., *f*(*α*) = 0, and f is differentiable in a neighborhood of α.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If f is continuously differentiable and its derivative is nonzero at α, then there exists a neighborhood of α such that for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence (*x**n*) will converge to α.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If f is continuously differentiable, its derivative is nonzero at α, *and* it has a second derivative at α, then the convergence is quadratic or faster.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If the second derivative is not 0 at α then the convergence is merely quadratic.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If the derivative is 0 at α, then the convergence is usually only linear.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Specifically, if f is twice continuously differentiable, *f′*(*α*) = 0 and *f″*(*α*) ≠ 0, then there exists a neighborhood of α such that, for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence of iterates converges linearly, with rate ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Alternatively, if *f′*(*α*) = 0 and *f′*(*x*) ≠ 0 for *x* ≠ *α*, x in a neighborhood U of α, α being a zero of multiplicity r, and if *f* ∈ *C**r*(*U*), then there exists a neighborhood of α such that, for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence of iterates converges linearly.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, even linear convergence is not guaranteed in pathological situations.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In practice, these results are local, and the neighborhood of convergence is not known in advance.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] But there are also some results on global convergence: for instance, given a right neighborhood *U*+ of α, if f is twice differentiable in *U*+ and if *f′* ≠ 0, *f* · *f″* > 0 in *U*+, then, for each *x*0 in *U*+ the sequence *x**k* is monotonically decreasing to α.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] According to Taylor's theorem, any function *f*(*x*) which has a continuous second derivative can be represented by an expansion about a point that is close to a root of *f*(*x*).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] where *ξ**n* is in between *x**n* and α.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Suppose that *f*(*x*) is a concave function on an interval, which is strictly increasing.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] If it is negative at the left endpoint and positive at the right endpoint, the intermediate value theorem guarantees that there is a zero ζ of f somewhere in the interval.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] From geometrical principles, it can be seen that the Newton iteration *x**i* starting at the left endpoint is monotonically increasing and convergent, necessarily to ζ.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This sequence is monotonically decreasing and convergent.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] By passing to the limit in this definition, it can be seen that the limit of *y**i* must also be the zero ζ.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] So, in the case of a concave increasing function with a zero, initialization is largely irrelevant.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton iteration starting anywhere left of the zero will converge, as will Fourier's modified Newton iteration starting anywhere right of the zero.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The accuracy at any step of the iteration can be determined directly from the difference between the location of the iteration from the left and the location of the iteration from the right.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] showing that this difference in locations converges quadratically to zero.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] All of the above can be extended to systems of equations in multiple variables, although in that context the relevant concepts of monotonicity and concavity are more subtle to formulate.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In the case of single equations in a single variable, the above monotonic convergence of Newton's method can also be generalized to replace concavity by positivity or negativity conditions on an arbitrary higher-order derivative of f.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] However, in this generalization, Newton's iteration is modified so as to be based on Taylor polynomials rather than the tangent line.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In the case of concavity, this modification coincides with the standard Newton method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Newton's method is one of many known methods of computing square roots.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Given a positive number a, the problem of finding a number x such that *x*2 = *a* is equivalent to finding a root of the function *f*(*x*) = *x*2 − *a*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This happens to coincide with the "Babylonian" method of finding square roots, which consists of replacing an approximate root *x**n* by the arithmetic mean of *x**n* and *a*⁄*x**n*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] By performing this iteration, it is possible to evaluate a square root to any desired accuracy by only using the basic arithmetic operations.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The following three tables show examples of the result of this computation for finding the square root of 612, with the iteration initialized at the values of 1, 10, and −20.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] It is seen that with only a few iterations one can obtain a solution accurate to many decimal places.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The first table shows that this is true even if the Newton iteration were initialized by the very inaccurate guess of 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] When computing any nonzero square root, the first derivative of f must be nonzero at the root, and that f is a smooth function.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] So, even before any computation, it is known that any convergent Newton iteration has a quadratic rate of convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] This is reflected in the above tables by the fact that once a Newton iterate gets close to the root, the number of correct digits approximately doubles with each iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Consider the problem of finding the positive number x with cos (*x*) = *x*3.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] We can rephrase that as finding the zero of *f*(*x*) = cos(*x*) − *x*3.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] Since cos(*x*) ≤ 1 for all x and *x*3 > 1 for *x* > 1, we know that our solution lies between 0 and 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] A starting value of 0 will lead to an undefined result which illustrates the importance of using a starting point close to the solution.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] The correct digits are underlined in the above example.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] In particular, *x*6 is correct to 12 decimal places.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p01] We see that the number of correct digits after the decimal point increases from 2 (for *x*3) to 5 and 10, illustrating the quadratic convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The k-dimensional variant of Newton's method can be used to solve systems of greater than k (nonlinear) equations as well if the algorithm uses the generalized inverse of the non-square Jacobian matrix *J*+ = (*J*T*J*)−1*J*T instead of the inverse of J.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] If the nonlinear system has no solution, the method attempts to find a solution in the non-linear least squares sense.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] See Gauss–Newton algorithm for more information.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] A milk carton with a capacity of 2 pints is to be constructed from a sheet of waxed carboard with a 5mm overlap.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The requirement is that the minimum surface area is used for the carton.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Suppose the width, breadth and height of the carton are denoted by w {\displaystyle w} ({\displaystyle w}), b {\displaystyle b} ({\displaystyle b}) and h {\displaystyle h} ({\displaystyle h}) respectively, in millimetres.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Since all eigenvalues are positive, J ( x 8 ) {\displaystyle \mathbf {J} (\mathbf {x} _{8})} ({\displaystyle \mathbf {J} (\mathbf {x} _{8})}) is positive definite, and therefore x 8 {\displaystyle \mathbf {x} _{8}} ({\displaystyle \mathbf {x} _{8}}) is a minimum.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] When dealing with complex functions, Newton's method can be directly applied to find their zeroes.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Each zero has a basin of attraction in the complex plane, the set of all starting values that cause the method to converge to that particular zero.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] These sets can be mapped as in the image shown.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] For many complex functions, the boundaries of the basins of attraction are fractals.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In some cases there are regions in the complex plane which are not in any of these basins of attraction, meaning the iterates do not converge.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] For example, if one uses a real initial condition to seek a root of *x*2 + 1, all subsequent iterates will be real numbers and so the iterations cannot converge to either root, since both roots are non-real.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In this case almost all real initial conditions lead to chaotic behavior, while some initial conditions iterate either to infinity or to repeating cycles of any finite length.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Curt McMullen has shown that for any possible purely iterative algorithm similar to Newton's method, the algorithm will diverge on some open regions of the complex plane when applied to some polynomial of degree 4 or higher.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] However, McMullen gave a generally convergent algorithm for polynomials of degree 3.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Also, for any polynomial, Hubbard, Schleicher, and Sutherland gave a method for selecting a set of initial points such that Newton's method will certainly converge at one of them at least.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Another generalization is Newton's method to find a root of a functional F defined in a Banach space.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] where *F′*(*X**n*) is the Fréchet derivative computed at *X**n*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] One needs the Fréchet derivative to be boundedly invertible at each *X**n* in order for the method to be applicable.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] A condition for existence of and convergence to a root is given by the Newton–Kantorovich theorem.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In the 1950s, John Nash developed a version of the Newton's method to apply to the problem of constructing isometric embeddings of general Riemannian manifolds in Euclidean space.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The *loss of derivatives* problem, present in this context, made the standard Newton iteration inapplicable, since it could not be continued indefinitely (much less converge).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Nash's solution involved the introduction of smoothing operators into the iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] He was able to prove the convergence of his smoothed Newton method, for the purpose of proving an implicit function theorem for isometric embeddings.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In the 1960s, Jürgen Moser showed that Nash's methods were flexible enough to apply to problems beyond isometric embedding, particularly in celestial mechanics.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Since then, a number of mathematicians, including Mikhael Gromov and Richard Hamilton, have found generalized abstract versions of the Nash–Moser theory.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In Hamilton's formulation, the Nash–Moser theorem forms a generalization of the Banach space Newton method which takes place in certain Fréchet spaces.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] When the Jacobian is unavailable or too expensive to compute at every iteration, a quasi-Newton method can be used.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Since higher-order Taylor expansions offer more accurate local approximations of a function f, it is reasonable to ask why Newton’s method relies only on a second-order Taylor approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In the 19th century, Russian mathematician Pafnuty Chebyshev explored this idea by developing a variant of Newton’s method that used cubic approximations.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] In p-adic analysis, the standard method to show a polynomial equation in one variable has a p-adic root is Hensel's lemma, which uses the recursion from Newton's method on the p-adic numbers.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Newton's method can be generalized with the q-analog of the usual derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] A nonlinear equation has multiple solutions in general.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] But if the initial value is not appropriate, Newton's method may not converge to the desired solution or may converge to the same solution found earlier.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] This method is applied to obtain zeros of the Bessel function of the second kind.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Hirano's modified Newton method is a modification conserving the convergence of Newton method and avoiding unstableness.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] It is developed to solve complex polynomials.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Combining Newton's method with interval arithmetic is very useful in some contexts.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] This provides a stopping criterion that is more reliable than the usual ones (which are a small value of the function or a small variation of the variable between consecutive iterations).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] We also assume that 0 ∉ *F′*(*X*), so in particular f has at most one root in X.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Note that the hypothesis on F′ implies that *N*(*Y*) is well defined and is an interval (see interval arithmetic for further details on interval operations).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The mean value theorem ensures that if there is a root of f in *X**k*, then it is also in *X**k* + 1.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Moreover, the hypothesis on F′ ensures that *X**k* + 1 is at most half the size of *X**k* when m is the midpoint of Y, so this sequence converges towards [*x**, *x**], where x* is the root of f in X.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] If *F′*(*X*) strictly contains 0, the use of extended interval division produces a union of two intervals for *N*(*X*); multiple roots are therefore automatically separated and bounded.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Newton's method can be used to find a minimum or maximum of a function *f*(*x*).
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The derivative is zero at a minimum or maximum, so local minima and maxima can be found by applying Newton's method to the derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] An important application is Newton–Raphson division, which can be used to quickly find the reciprocal of a number a, using only multiplication and subtraction, that is to say the number x such that ⁠1/*x*⁠ = *a*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] We can rephrase that as finding the zero of *f*(*x*) = ⁠1/*x*⁠ − *a*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Therefore, Newton's iteration needs only two multiplications and one subtraction.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] This method is also very efficient to compute the multiplicative inverse of a power series.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Many transcendental equations can be solved up to an arbitrary precision by using Newton's method.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] For example, finding the cumulative probability density function, such as a Normal distribution to fit a known probability generally involves integral functions with no known means to solve in closed form.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] However, computing the derivatives needed to solve them numerically with Newton's method is generally known, making numerical solutions possible.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] For an example, see the numerical solution to the inverse Normal cumulative distribution.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] A numerical verification for solutions of nonlinear equations has been established by using Newton's method multiple times and forming a set of solution candidates.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The following is an example of a possible implementation of Newton's method in the Python (version 3.x) programming language for finding a root of a function `f` which has derivative `f_prime`.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] The initial guess will be *x*0 = 1 and the function will be *f*(*x*) = *x*2 − 2 so that *f′*(*x*) = 2*x*.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] Each new iteration of Newton's method will be denoted by `x1`.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method-p02] We will check during the computation whether the denominator (`y_prime`) becomes too small (smaller than `epsilon`), which would be the case if *f′*(*x**n*) ≈ 0, since otherwise a large amount of error could be introduced.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method] The process can be started with any arbitrary initial guess ⁠ $x_{0}$ ⁠, though it will generally require fewer iterations to converge if the guess is close to one of the function's roots.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method] The method will usually converge if ⁠ $f'(x_{0})\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:numerical-methods/newton-s-method] However, the extra computations required for each step can slow down the overall performance relative to Newton's method, particularly if ⁠ f ⁠ or its derivatives are computationally expensive to evaluate.
