[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis finds application in all fields of engineering and the physical sciences, and in the 21st century also the life and social sciences like economics, medicine, business and even the arts.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Current growth in computing power has enabled the use of more complex numerical analysis, providing detailed and realistic mathematical models in science and engineering.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Before modern computers, numerical methods often relied on hand interpolation formulas, using data from large printed tables.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Since the mid-20th century, computers calculate the required functions instead, but many of the same formulas continue to be used in software algorithms.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The numerical point of view goes back to the earliest mathematical writings.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] A tablet from the Yale Babylonian Collection (YBC 7289), gives a sexagesimal numerical approximation of the square root of 2, the length of the diagonal in a unit square.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis continues this long tradition: rather than giving exact symbolic answers translated into digits and applicable only to real-world measurements, approximate solutions within specified error bounds are used.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis predates the invention of modern computers by many centuries.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Linear interpolation was already in use more than 2000 years ago.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Many great mathematicians of the past were preoccupied by numerical analysis, as is obvious from the names of important algorithms like Newton's method, Lagrange interpolation polynomial, Gaussian elimination, or Euler's method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The origins of modern numerical analysis are often linked to a 1947 paper by John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine, but others consider modern numerical analysis to go back to work by E.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] To facilitate computations by hand, large books were produced with formulas and tables of data such as interpolation points and function coefficients.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Using these tables, often calculated out to 16 decimal places or more for some functions, one could look up values to plug into the formulas given and achieve very good numerical estimates of some functions.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The canonical work in the field is the NIST publication edited by Abramowitz and Stegun, a 1000-plus page book of a very large number of commonly used formulas and functions and their values at many points.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The function values are no longer very useful when a computer is available, but the large listing of formulas can still be very handy.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The mechanical calculator was also developed as a tool for hand computation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] These calculators evolved into electronic computers in the 1940s, and it was then found that these computers were also useful for administrative purposes.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] But the invention of the computer also influenced the field of numerical analysis, since now longer and more complicated calculations could be done.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The Leslie Fox Prize for Numerical Analysis was initiated in 1985 by the Institute of Mathematics and its Applications.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Direct methods compute the solution to a problem in a finite number of steps.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] These methods would give the precise answer if they were performed in infinite precision arithmetic.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Examples include Gaussian elimination, the QR factorization method for solving systems of linear equations, and the simplex method of linear programming.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] In practice, finite precision is used and the result is an approximation of the true solution (assuming stability).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] In contrast to direct methods, iterative methods are not expected to terminate in a finite number of steps, even if infinite precision were possible.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Starting from an initial guess, iterative methods form successive approximations that converge to the exact solution only in the limit.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] A convergence test, often involving the residual, is specified in order to decide when a sufficiently accurate solution has (hopefully) been found.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Even using infinite precision arithmetic these methods would not reach the solution within a finite number of steps (in general).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Examples include Newton's method, the bisection method, and Jacobi iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] In computational matrix algebra, iterative methods are generally needed for large problems.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods are more common than direct methods in numerical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Some methods are direct in principle but are usually used as though they were not, e.g.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] GMRES and the conjugate gradient method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For these methods the number of steps needed to obtain the exact solution is so large that an approximation is accepted in the same manner as for an iterative method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For the iterative method, apply the bisection method to *f*(*x*) = 3*x*3 − 24.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] From this table it can be concluded that the solution is between 1.875 and 2.0625.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The algorithm might return any number in that range with an error less than 0.2.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Ill-conditioned problem: Take the function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Evaluating *f*(*x*) near *x* = 1 is an ill-conditioned problem.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Well-conditioned problem: By contrast, evaluating the same function *f*(*x*) = 1/(*x* − 1) near *x* = 10 is a well-conditioned problem.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Furthermore, continuous problems must sometimes be replaced by a discrete problem whose solution is known to approximate that of the continuous problem; this process is called 'discretization'.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For example, the solution of a differential equation is a function.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] This function must be represented by a finite amount of data, for instance by its value at a finite number of points at its domain, even though this domain is a continuum.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The study of errors forms an important part of numerical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] There are several ways in which error can be introduced in the solution of the problem.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Round-off errors arise because it is impossible to represent all real numbers exactly on a machine with finite memory (which is what all practical digital computers are).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Truncation errors are committed when an iterative method is terminated or a mathematical procedure is approximated and the approximate solution differs from the exact solution.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Similarly, discretization induces a discretization error because the solution of the discrete problem does not coincide with the solution of the continuous problem.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] In the example above to compute the solution of $3x^{3}+4=28$ , after ten iterations, the calculated root is roughly 1.99.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Therefore, the truncation error is roughly 0.01.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Once an error is generated, it propagates through the calculation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For example, the operation + on a computer is inexact.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] A calculation of the type ⁠ $a+b+c+d+e$ ⁠ is even more inexact.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] A truncation error is created when a mathematical procedure is approximated.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] To integrate a function exactly, an infinite sum of regions must be found, but numerically only a finite sum of regions can be found, and hence the approximation of the exact solution.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Similarly, to differentiate a function, the differential element approaches zero, but numerically only a nonzero value of the differential element can be chosen.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] An algorithm is called *numerically stable* if an error, whatever its cause, does not grow to be much larger during the calculation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] This happens if the problem is *well-conditioned*, meaning that the solution changes by only a small amount if the problem data are changed by a small amount.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] To the contrary, if a problem is 'ill-conditioned', then any small error in the data will grow to be a large error.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Both the original problem and the algorithm used to solve that problem can be well-conditioned or ill-conditioned, and any combination is possible.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] So an algorithm that solves a well-conditioned problem may be either numerically stable or numerically unstable.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] An art of numerical analysis is to find a stable algorithm for solving a well-posed mathematical problem.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The field of numerical analysis includes many sub-disciplines.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] One of the simplest problems is the evaluation of a function at a given point.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The most straightforward approach, of just plugging in the number in the formula is sometimes not very efficient.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For polynomials, a better approach is using the Horner scheme, since it reduces the necessary number of multiplications and additions.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Generally, it is important to estimate and control round-off errors arising from the use of floating-point arithmetic.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Interpolation solves the following problem: given the value of some unknown function at a number of points, what value does that function have at some other point between the given points?
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Extrapolation is very similar to interpolation, except that now the value of the unknown function at a point which is outside the given points must be found.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Regression is also similar, but it takes into account that the data are imprecise.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Given some points, and a measurement of the value of some function at these points (with an error), the unknown function can be found.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The least squares-method is one way to achieve this.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Another fundamental problem is computing the solution of some given equation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Two cases are commonly distinguished, depending on whether the equation is linear or not.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For instance, the equation $2x+5=3$ is linear while $2x^{2}+5=3$ is not.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Much effort has been put in the development of methods for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Standard direct methods, i.e., methods that use some matrix decomposition are Gaussian elimination, LU decomposition, Cholesky decomposition for symmetric (or hermitian) and positive-definite matrix, and QR decomposition for non-square matrices.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Iterative methods such as the Jacobi method, Gauss–Seidel method, successive over-relaxation and conjugate gradient method are usually preferred for large systems.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] General iterative methods can be developed using a matrix splitting.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Root-finding algorithms are used to solve nonlinear equations (they are so named since a root of a function is an argument for which the function yields zero).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] If the function is differentiable and the derivative is known, then Newton's method is a popular choice.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Linearization is another technique for solving nonlinear equations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Several important problems can be phrased in terms of eigenvalue decompositions or singular value decompositions.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For instance, the spectral image compression algorithm is based on the singular value decomposition.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The corresponding tool in statistics is called principal component analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Optimization problems ask for the point at which a given function is maximized (or minimized).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Often, the point also has to satisfy some constraints.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The field of optimization is further split in several subfields, depending on the form of the objective function and the constraint.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] For instance, linear programming deals with the case that both the objective function and the constraints are linear.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] A famous method in linear programming is the simplex method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The method of Lagrange multipliers can be used to reduce optimization problems with constraints to unconstrained optimization problems.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Numerical integration, in some instances also known as numerical quadrature, asks for the value of a definite integral.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Popular methods use one of the Newton–Cotes formulas (like the midpoint rule or Simpson's rule) or Gaussian quadrature.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] These methods rely on a "divide and conquer" strategy, whereby an integral on a relatively large set is broken down into integrals on smaller sets.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] In higher dimensions, where these methods become prohibitively expensive in terms of computational effort, one may use Monte Carlo or quasi-Monte Carlo methods (see Monte Carlo integration), or, in modestly large dimensions, the method of sparse grids.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Numerical analysis is also concerned with computing (in an approximate way) the solution of differential equations, both ordinary differential equations and partial differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Partial differential equations are solved by first discretizing the equation, bringing it into a finite-dimensional subspace.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] This can be done by a finite element method, a finite difference method, or (particularly in engineering) a finite volume method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The theoretical justification of these methods often involves theorems from functional analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] This reduces the problem to the solution of an algebraic equation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Since the late twentieth century, most algorithms are implemented in a variety of programming languages.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The Netlib repository contains various collections of software routines for numerical problems, mostly in Fortran and C.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Commercial products implementing many different numerical algorithms include the IMSL and NAG libraries; a free-software alternative is the GNU Scientific Library.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Over the years the Royal Statistical Society published numerous algorithms in its *Applied Statistics* (code for these "AS" functions is here); ACM similarly, in its *Transactions on Mathematical Software* ("TOMS" code is here).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] The Naval Surface Warfare Center several times published its *Library of Mathematics Subroutines* (code here).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] There are several popular numerical computing applications such as MATLAB, TK Solver, S-PLUS, and IDL as well as free and open-source alternatives such as FreeMat, Scilab, GNU Octave (similar to Matlab), and IT++ (a C++ library).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] There are also programming languages such as R (similar to S-PLUS), Julia, and Python with libraries such as NumPy, SciPy and SymPy.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Performance varies widely: while vector and matrix operations are usually fast, scalar loops may vary in speed by more than an order of magnitude.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Many computer algebra systems such as Mathematica also benefit from the availability of arbitrary-precision arithmetic which can provide more accurate results.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Also, any spreadsheet software can be used to solve simple problems relating to numerical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-analysis] Excel, for example, has hundreds of available functions, including for matrices, which may be used in conjunction with its built in "solver".
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:numerical-methods/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] In numerical analysis, a **root-finding algorithm** is an algorithm for finding zeros, also called "roots", of continuous functions.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] A zero of a function *f* is a number *x* such that *f*(*x*) = 0.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] As, generally, the zeros of a function cannot be computed exactly nor expressed in closed form, root-finding algorithms provide approximations to zeros.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] For functions from the real numbers to real numbers or from the complex numbers to the complex numbers, these are expressed either as floating-point numbers without error bounds or as floating-point values together with error bounds.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The latter, approximations with error bounds, are equivalent to small isolating intervals for real roots or disks for complex roots.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Thus root-finding algorithms can be used to solve any equation of continuous functions.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, most root-finding algorithms do not guarantee that they will find all roots of a function, and if such an algorithm does not find any root, that does not necessarily mean that no root exists.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Most numerical root-finding methods are iterative methods, producing a sequence of numbers that ideally converges towards a root as a limit.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] They require one or more *initial guesses* of the root as starting values, then each iteration of the algorithm produces a successively more accurate approximation to the root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Since the iteration must be stopped at some point, these methods produce an approximation to the root, not an exact solution.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Many methods compute subsequent values by evaluating an auxiliary function on the preceding values.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The limit is thus a fixed point of the auxiliary function, which is chosen for having the roots of the original equation as fixed points and for converging rapidly to these fixed points.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The behavior of general root-finding algorithms is studied in numerical analysis.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, for polynomials specifically, the study of root-finding algorithms belongs to computer algebra, since algebraic properties of polynomials are fundamental for the most efficient algorithms.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The efficiency and applicability of an algorithm may depend sensitively on the characteristics of the given functions.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] For example, many algorithms use the derivative of the input function, while others work on every continuous function.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] In general, numerical algorithms are not guaranteed to find all the roots of a function, so failing to find a root does not prove that there is no root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Bracketing methods determine successively smaller intervals (brackets) that contain a root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] When the interval is small enough, then a root is considered found.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] These generally use the intermediate value theorem, which asserts that if a continuous function has values of opposite signs at the end points of an interval, then the function has at least one root in the interval.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Therefore, they require starting with an interval such that the function takes opposite signs at the end points of the interval.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, in the case of polynomials there are other methods such as Descartes' rule of signs, Budan's theorem and Sturm's theorem for bounding or determining the number of roots in an interval.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] They lead to efficient algorithms for real-root isolation of polynomials, which find all real roots with a guaranteed accuracy.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The simplest root-finding algorithm is the bisection method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Let *f* be a continuous function for which one knows an interval [*a*, *b*] such that *f*(*a*) and *f*(*b*) have opposite signs (a bracket).
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Let *c* = (*a* + *b*)/2 be the middle of the interval (the midpoint or the point that bisects the interval).
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Then either *f*(*a*) and *f*(*c*), or *f*(*c*) and *f*(*b*) have opposite signs, and one has divided by two the size of the interval.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Although the bisection method is robust, it gains one and only one bit of accuracy with each iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Therefore, the number of function evaluations required for finding an *ε*-approximate root is $\log _{2}{\frac {b-a}{\varepsilon }}$ .
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Other methods, under appropriate conditions, can gain accuracy faster.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] False position is similar to the secant method, except that, instead of retaining the last two points, it makes sure to keep one point on either side of the root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The false position method can be faster than the bisection method and will never diverge like the secant method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, it may fail to converge in some naive implementations due to roundoff errors that may lead to a wrong sign for *f*(*c*).
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Typically, this may occur if the derivative of f is large in the neighborhood of the root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Many root-finding processes work by interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This consists in using the last computed approximate values of the root for approximating the function by a polynomial of low degree, which takes the same values at these approximate roots.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Then the root of the polynomial is computed and used as a new approximate value of the root of the function, and the process is iterated.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Interpolating two values yields a line: a polynomial of degree one.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] *Regula falsi* is also an interpolation method that interpolates two points at a time but it differs from the secant method by using two points that are not necessarily the last two computed points.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Three values define a parabolic curve: a quadratic function.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Although all root-finding algorithms proceed by iteration, an iterative root-finding method generally uses a specific type of iteration, consisting of defining an auxiliary function, which is applied to the last computed approximations of a root for getting a new approximation.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The iteration stops when a fixed point of the auxiliary function is reached to the desired precision, i.e., when a new computed value is sufficiently close to the preceding ones.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method assumes the function *f* to have a continuous derivative.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method may not converge if started too far away from a root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, when it does converge, it is faster than the bisection method; its order of convergence is usually quadratic whereas the bisection method's is linear.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method is also important because it readily generalizes to higher-dimensional problems.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Householder's methods are a class of Newton-like methods with higher orders of convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The first one after Newton's method is Halley's method with cubic order of convergence.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Replacing the derivative in Newton's method with a finite difference, we get the secant method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This method does not require the computation (nor the existence) of a derivative, but the price is slower convergence (the order of convergence is the golden ratio, approximately 1.62).
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] A generalization of the secant method in higher dimensions is Broyden's method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] We can use the fixed-point iteration to find the root of a function.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Given a function $f(x)$ which we have set to zero to find the root ( $f(x)=0$ ), we rewrite the equation in terms of x so that $f(x)=0$ becomes $x=g(x)$ (note, there are often many $g(x)$ functions for each $f(x)=0$ function).
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Next, we relabel each side of the equation as $x_{n+1}=g(x_{n})$ so that we can perform the iteration.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Next, we pick a value for $x_{1}$ and perform the iteration until it converges towards a root of the function.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] If the iteration converges, it will converge to a root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The iteration will only converge if $|g'(root)|<1$ .
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] As an example of converting $f(x)=0$ to $x=g(x)$ , if given the function $f(x)=x^{2}+x-1$ , we will rewrite it as one of the following equations.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The appearance of complex values in interpolation methods can be avoided by interpolating the inverse of *f*, resulting in the inverse quadratic interpolation method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Again, convergence is asymptotically faster than the secant method, but inverse quadratic interpolation often behaves poorly when the iterates are not close to the root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Brent's method is a combination of the bisection method, the secant method and inverse quadratic interpolation.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] At every iteration, Brent's method decides which method out of these three is likely to do best, and proceeds by doing a step according to that method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This gives a robust and fast method, which therefore enjoys considerable popularity.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Ridders' method is a hybrid method that uses the value of function at the midpoint of the interval to perform an exponential interpolation to the root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This gives a fast convergence with a guaranteed convergence of at most twice the number of iterations as the bisection method.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Finding the roots of polynomials is a long-standing problem that has been extensively studied throughout the history and substantially influenced the development of mathematics.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] where $a_{i}$ are either real or complex numbers.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Efforts to understand and solve polynomial equations led to the development of important mathematical concepts, including irrational and complex numbers, as well as foundational structures in modern algebra such as fields, rings, and groups.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Despite being historically important, finding the roots of higher degree polynomials no longer play a central role in mathematics and computational mathematics, with one major exception in computer algebra.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The bisection method has been generalized to higher dimensions; these methods are called **generalized bisection methods**.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] At each iteration, the domain is partitioned into two parts, and the algorithm decides - based on a small number of function evaluations - which of these two parts must contain a root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] In one dimension, the criterion for decision is that the function has opposite signs.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The main challenge in extending the method to multiple dimensions is to find a criterion that can be computed easily and guarantees the existence of a root.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The Poincaré–Miranda theorem gives a criterion for the existence of a root in a rectangle, but it is hard to verify because it requires evaluating the function on the entire boundary of the rectangle.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Another criterion is given by a theorem of Kronecker.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] It says that, if the topological degree of a function *f* on a rectangle is non-zero, then the rectangle must contain at least one root of *f*.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This criterion is the basis for several root-finding methods, such as those of Stenger and Kearfott.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] However, computing the topological degree can be time-consuming.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] A third criterion is based on a *characteristic polyhedron*.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] This criterion is used by a method called Characteristic Bisection.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] It does not require computing the topological degree; it only requires computing the signs of function values.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] The number of required evaluations is at least $\log _{2}(D/\epsilon )$ , where *D* is the length of the longest edge of the characteristic polyhedron.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Note that Vrahatis and Iordanidis prove a lower bound on the number of evaluations, and not an upper bound.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] A fourth method uses an intermediate value theorem on simplices.
[src:numerical-methods/root-finding-algorithm] Again, no upper bound on the number of queries is given.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In numerical analysis, the **Runge–Kutta methods** (English: /ˈrʊŋəˈkʊtɑː/ ⓘ *RUUNG-ə-KUUT-tah*) are a family of implicit and explicit iterative methods, which include the Euler method, used in temporal discretization for the approximate solutions of simultaneous nonlinear equations.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] These methods were developed around 1900 by the German mathematicians Carl Runge and Wilhelm Kutta.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The most widely known member of the Runge–Kutta family is generally referred to as "RK4", the "classic Runge–Kutta method" or simply as "the Runge–Kutta method".
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] At the initial time t 0 {\displaystyle t_{0}} ({\displaystyle t_{0}}) the corresponding y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}) value is y 0 {\displaystyle y_{0}} ({\displaystyle y_{0}}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The function f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) and the initial conditions t 0 {\displaystyle t_{0}} ({\displaystyle t_{0}}), y 0 {\displaystyle y_{0}} ({\displaystyle y_{0}}) are given.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In averaging the four slopes, greater weight is given to the slopes at the midpoint.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] If f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) is independent of y {\displaystyle y} ({\displaystyle y}), so that the differential equation is equivalent to a simple integral, then RK4 is Simpson's rule.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The RK4 method is a fourth-order method, meaning that the local truncation error is on the order of O ( h 5 ) {\displaystyle O(h^{5})} ({\displaystyle O(h^{5})}), while the total accumulated error is on the order of O ( h 4 ) {\displaystyle O(h^{4})} ({\displaystyle O(h^{4})}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The family of explicit Runge–Kutta methods is a generalization of the RK4 method mentioned above.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Note: the above equations may have different but equivalent definitions in some texts.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] To specify a particular method, one needs to provide the integer *s* (the number of stages), and the coefficients *aij* (for 1 ≤ *j* < *i* ≤ *s*), *bi* (for *i* = 1, 2, ..., *s*) and *ci* (for *i* = 2, 3, ..., *s*).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The matrix [*aij*] is called the *Runge–Kutta matrix*, while the *bi* and *ci* are known as the *weights* and the *nodes*.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] These data are usually arranged in a mnemonic device, known as a *Butcher tableau* (after John C.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] There are also accompanying requirements if one requires the method to have a certain order *p*, meaning that the local truncation error is O(*hp*+1).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] These can be derived from the definition of the truncation error itself.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This condition alone, however, is neither sufficient, nor necessary for consistency.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] However, it is not known whether these bounds are *sharp* in all cases.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In some cases, it is proven that the bound cannot be achieved.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] For instance, Butcher proved that for p > 6 {\displaystyle p>6} ({\displaystyle p>6}), there is no explicit method with s = p + 1 {\displaystyle s=p+1} ({\displaystyle s=p+1}) stages.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Butcher also proved that for p > 7 {\displaystyle p>7} ({\displaystyle p>7}), there is no explicit Runge-Kutta method with p + 2 {\displaystyle p+2} ({\displaystyle p+2}) stages.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In general, however, it remains an open problem what the precise minimum number of stages s {\displaystyle s} ({\displaystyle s}) is for an explicit Runge–Kutta method to have order p {\displaystyle p} ({\displaystyle p}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The provable bound above then implies that we cannot find methods of orders p = 1 , 2 , … , 6 {\displaystyle p=1,2,\ldots ,6} ({\displaystyle p=1,2,\ldots ,6}) that require fewer stages than the methods we already know for these orders.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The work of Butcher also proves that 7th and 8th order methods have a minimum of 9 and 11 stages, respectively.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] An example of an explicit method of order 6 with 7 stages can be found in Ref.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Explicit methods of order 7 with 9 stages and explicit methods of order 8 with 11 stages are also known.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] A slight variation of "the" Runge–Kutta method is also due to Kutta in 1901 and is called the 3/8-rule.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The primary advantage this method has is that almost all of the error coefficients are smaller than in the popular method, but it requires slightly more floating-point operations per time step.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] However, the simplest Runge–Kutta method is the (forward) Euler method, given by the formula y n + 1 = y n + h f ( t n , y n ) {\displaystyle y_{n+1}=y_{n}+hf(t_{n},y_{n})} ({\displaystyle y_{n+1}=y_{n}+hf(t_{n},y_{n})}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This is the only consistent explicit Runge–Kutta method with one stage.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] As an example, consider the two-stage second-order Runge–Kutta method with α = 2/3, also known as Ralston method.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] with step size *h* = 0.025, so the method needs to take four steps.
