[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Explicit Runge–Kutta methods are generally unsuitable for the solution of stiff equations because their region of absolute stability is small; in particular, it is bounded.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This issue is especially important in the solution of partial differential equations.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The instability of explicit Runge–Kutta methods motivates the development of implicit methods.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The difference with an explicit method is that in an explicit method, the sum over *j* only goes up to *i* − 1.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This also shows up in the Butcher tableau: the coefficient matrix a i j {\displaystyle a_{ij}} ({\displaystyle a_{ij}}) of an explicit method is lower triangular.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The consequence of this difference is that at every step, a system of algebraic equations has to be solved.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This increases the computational cost considerably.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] If a method with *s* stages is used to solve a differential equation with *m* components, then the system of algebraic equations has *ms* components.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] which can be re-arranged to get the formula for the backward Euler method listed above.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Another example for an implicit Runge–Kutta method is the trapezoidal rule.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The trapezoidal rule is a collocation method (as discussed in that article).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] All collocation methods are implicit Runge–Kutta methods, but not all implicit Runge–Kutta methods are collocation methods.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The Gauss–Legendre methods form a family of collocation methods based on Gauss quadrature.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] A Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s* (thus, methods with arbitrarily high order can be constructed).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The advantage of implicit Runge–Kutta methods over explicit ones is their greater stability, especially when applied to stiff equations.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Consider the linear test equation y ′ = λ y {\displaystyle y'=\lambda y} ({\displaystyle y'=\lambda y}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] where *e* stands for the vector of ones.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The function *r* is called the *stability function*.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] It follows from the formula that *r* is the quotient of two polynomials of degree *s* if the method has *s* stages.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Explicit methods have a strictly lower triangular matrix *A*, which implies that det(*I* − *zA*) = 1 and that the stability function is a polynomial.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The numerical solution to the linear test equation decays to zero if | *r*(*z*) | < 1 with *z* = *h*λ.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The set of such *z* is called the *domain of absolute stability*.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In particular, the method is said to be absolute stable if all *z* with Re(*z*) < 0 are in the domain of absolute stability.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The stability function of an explicit Runge–Kutta method is a polynomial, so explicit Runge–Kutta methods can never be A-stable.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Thus, it is of interest to study quotients of polynomials of given degrees that approximate the exponential function the best.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] A Padé approximant with numerator of degree *m* and denominator of degree *n* is A-stable if and only if *m* ≤ *n* ≤ *m* + 2.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] The Gauss–Legendre method with *s* stages has order 2*s*, so its stability function is the Padé approximant with *m* = *n* = *s*.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This shows that A-stable Runge–Kutta can have arbitrarily high order.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] In contrast, the order of A-stable linear multistep methods cannot exceed two.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Adaptive methods are designed to produce an estimate of the local truncation error of a single Runge–Kutta step.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This is done by having two methods, one with order p {\displaystyle p} ({\displaystyle p}) and one with order p − 1 {\displaystyle p-1} ({\displaystyle p-1}).
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] These methods are interwoven, i.e., they have common intermediate steps.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Thanks to this, estimating the error has little or negligible computational cost compared to a step with the higher-order method.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] During the integration, the step size is adapted such that the estimated error stays below a user-defined threshold: If the error is too high, a step is repeated with a lower step size; if the error is much smaller, the step size is increased to save time.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] This results in an (almost), optimal step size, which saves computation time.
[src:numerical-methods/runge-kutta-methods-p01] Moreover, the user does not have to spend time on finding an appropriate step size.
